The golden ratio $\varphi = \frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}$ satisfies the
equations $$\begin{aligned}
\begin{cases}
\varphi\!+\!1 \;=\; \varphi^2, \\
\varphi\!-\!1 \;=\; \varphi^{-1}
\end{cases}\end{aligned}$$ from which the latter is obained from the
former by dividing by $\varphi$. There is a pair of equations satisfied
by the plastic number $P$: $$\begin{aligned}
\begin{cases}
P\!+\!1 \;=\; P^3, \\
P\!-\!1 \;=\; P^{-4}
\end{cases}\end{aligned}$$ Here, the latter equation is justified by
$$P^5\!-\!P^4\!-\!1 \;\equiv\; (\underbrace{P^3\!-\!P\!-\!1}_{=\;0})(P^2\!-\!P\!+\!1)$$
when this is divided by $P^4$.\
An algebraic integer is called a *morphic number*, iff it satisfies a
pair of equations $$\begin{aligned}
\begin{cases}
x\!+\!1 \;=\; x^m, \\
x\!-\!1 \;=\; x^{-n}
\end{cases}\end{aligned}$$ for some positive integers $m$ and $n$.\
Accordingly, the golden ratio and the plastic number are morphic
numbers. It can be shown that there are no other real morphic numbers
greater than 1.

